==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₁rewdʰ-}}
From {{confix|en|erythro|cyte|gloss1=red|gloss2=cell}}, referring to the red color of [[hemoglobin]] when oxygen is bound to it.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/əˈɹɪθɹəˌsaɪt/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|hematology|cytology}} An [[anucleate]] [[hemoglobin]]-containing [[cell]], especially as found in humans but more generally present in the [[blood]] of most [[vertebrate]]s, that is involved with the transport of [[oxygen]]; a [[red blood cell]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=23 March 1901|page=742|title=The name of the red corpuscle: a suggestion|passage=The want of  success of these names may be attributed to their awkwardness in sound or  sense; "'''erythrocyte'''" seems the best of them, but is unfortunately four-syllabled.|author=Ch. S. Sherrington|journal=British Medical Journal}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=September 1901|author=C. Y. White|journal=The American Journal of the Medical Sciences|volume=122|issue=3|title=Granular degeneration of the erythrocyte|passage=Granular, basic, or punctate degeneration of the '''erythrocyte''' is a condition in which this cell presents fine or coarse granules that have an affinity for basic stains.}}

